Streaming Residuals and Spotify
-------------------------------

I also made a second error when I lazily referred to broadcast residuals in=
creasing based on a show=E2=80=99s popularity; that isn=E2=80=99t strictly =
true, as residuals are paid based on the number of times an episode or movi=
e is shown, not on whatever rating it gets (of course the number of times a=
n episode or movie is shown is a function of popularity). This model was ro=
ughly translated to streaming, wherein a show is paid residuals for being o=
n a service (and thus =E2=80=9Cshown=E2=80=9D); the payout is a function of=
 the size of the streaming service=E2=80=99s subscriber base (the WGA has a=
 breakdown of residual payouts on streaming services here ( https://www.wga=
.org/members/finances/residuals/hbsvod-programs ) ; the SGA=E2=80=99s payou=
ts function similarly).

The Washington Post had a useful article about residuals ( https://www.wash=
ingtonpost.com/lifestyle/2023/07/15/actors-strike-what-are-residuals/ ) , e=
xplaining the strikers=E2=80=99 consternation with streaming services:

The advent of streaming has led to significantly lower residuals, according=
 to SAG-AFTRA. During the heyday of cable TV, near-constant reruns of popul=
ar shows meant big residual paydays for writers and actors. But the meteori=
c rise of streaming services such as Netflix and Hulu has upended that real=
ity, and creators say residuals are shrinking. Unlike cable reruns, residua=
l payments for streaming services aren=E2=80=99t based on the number of tim=
es an episode or movie is viewed. Instead, they=E2=80=99re based on the num=
ber of subscribers the streaming service has, according to WGA. So writers =
and actors who work for platforms like Netflix make more than those who wor=
k for smaller streamers like Paramount Plus.

That means that regardless of whether a show is a flop or a cash cow, it ma=
kes the same amount in residuals. Writers and actors say that allows studio=
s to profit off of their work without compensating them fairly for the succ=
ess of a show. In short: Studios are making more off shows because of strea=
ming, while writers and actors say they are making less. That, combined wit=
h inflation, has led to unfair compensation, SAG-AFTRA argues.

Reality is, as this article in Deadline explains ( https://deadline.com/202=
3/04/hollywood-strike-streaming-residuals-wga-producers-1235325130/ ) , mor=
e complicated:

Last week, the WGA=E2=80=99s Negotiating Committee, in its latest appeal to=
 members to approve a strike authorization, said, =E2=80=9COver the past de=
cade, while our employers have increased their profits by tens of billions,=
 they have embraced business practices that have slashed our compensation a=
nd residuals and undermined our working conditions.=E2=80=9D But the WGA We=
st=E2=80=99s latest annual report, released in June, notes that for the fis=
cal year ended March 31, 2022, total residuals collected by the guild in 20=
21 hit an =E2=80=9Call-time high.=E2=80=9D The guild=E2=80=99s annual repor=
ts also show that total residuals increased by 48.2% from 2011 to 2021 =E2=
=80=93 from $333 million to $493.6 million.

Charles Slocum, assistant executive director at the WGA West, told Deadline=
 this week that =E2=80=9Ctotal residuals are higher because many more proje=
cts are being made, and a lot more are in reuse.=E2=80=9D The =E2=80=9Cslas=
hing=E2=80=9D of residuals, he said, =E2=80=9Cis on a per-program basis.=E2=
=80=9D And the culprit is streaming, where half of all series writers now w=
ork.

=E2=80=9CIn streaming, the companies have not agreed to pay residuals at th=
e same level as broadcast, or the same reward-for-success as they have trad=
itionally paid in broadcast,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIf you write for a =
streamer, you get two residuals payments =E2=80=93 one for domestic streami=
ng and one for foreign streaming. It=E2=80=99s a set amount of money. If it=
=E2=80=99s a big hit, you do not get paid more residuals in streaming, wher=
eas in the broadcast model, you do because of its success. That=E2=80=99s t=
he sense that residuals were slashed =E2=80=93 they have not agreed to a su=
ccess factor when a program is made for streaming.=E2=80=9D

This is in fact a concrete example of how the inherent abundance of streami=
ng, which is unmoored from the time limitations of linear TV, has had a dra=
matic effect: the studios can (correctly) argue that residual payouts have =
increased significantly, because they are considering the total; abundance,=
 though, means more competition, which makes the payouts feel like less for=
 individuals.

This dynamic may sound familiar:

RIAA revenue over time ( https://www.riaa.com/u-s-sales-database/ )

This revenue tracker from the RIAA ( https://www.riaa.com/u-s-sales-databas=
e/ ) is one I have referenced before: note that the music industry, for all=
 of its challenges in the 2000s, is now grossing more than it did in the he=
yday of the CD (before an adjustment for inflation, to be fair). The driver=
 is the dramatic rise in streaming revenue, and yet the complaint we hear a=
bout streaming is that it is a bad deal for artists, who are paid fractions=
 of a penny for every song. Once again the dichotomy is between aggregate r=
evenue, which this chart shows, and per-artist revenue, which on an average=
 basis is almost certainly lower because there are far more artists than ev=
er before, because there is an abundance of music.

What is interesting to consider is if this comparison might go further and =
point to a potential resolution of this strike, at least in terms of the re=
siduals question. Keep in mind that artists are not paid on a per-stream ba=
sis. Rather there is a pool of money that is set aside for artists (primari=
ly via contracts with the music labels), and that pool is split up based on=
 an artists=E2=80=99 share of total streams. To use a dramatically simplifi=
ed example:

* If Spotify has $1,000,000 in revenue and,
* Labels get 60% of that revenue and,
* Taylor Swift has 1% of total Spotify streams then,

Swift=E2=80=99s payout would be $1,000,000 =C3=97 60% =C3=97 1% =3D $6,000.=
 Notably this payout is only indirectly linked to the total number of strea=
ms of Swift=E2=80=99s music; what matters is Swift=E2=80=99s stream share o=
f the absolute total.

